#!/usr/bin/env python3
# crack -- Lab 8 Part 1: a dictionary attack on a stolen store.  STARTER.
#
#   crack <storefile> <wordlist>
#
# Given a store you generated and a wordlist, recover every password that is in
# the wordlist, and report how much WORK it took.  The work is `hash_ops`: the
# number of KDF evaluations you perform.  It is the deterministic heart of the
# salting lesson and does not depend on your hardware:
#
#   * Against an UNSALTED store, hash each of the W words ONCE into a
#     digest->word table, then look every user up for free.  hash_ops = W,
#     whatever the number of users N.
#   * Against a SALTED (or slow) store, every user has a different salt, so the
#     table cannot be shared: re-hash all W words for each of the N users.
#     hash_ops = W * N.
#
# Scan the whole wordlist for each salted user (do not stop at the first hit) so
# hash_ops is a clean W or W*N regardless of which passwords are present.
#
# Wall-clock time is reported too but is only rubric-marked; hash_ops is the
# number to reason about.  Keep the two output lines below exactly as written.

